WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:12.480
Throughout history, moments of scientific discovery have not just changed what we know,

00:12.480 --> 00:14.320
but how we think.

00:14.320 --> 00:19.680
Today, we explore the transformative power of the scientific revolution on European

00:19.680 --> 00:25.560
thought and its lasting influence on modern society.

00:25.560 --> 00:30.640
In the 16th century, Copernicus proposed a radical idea.

00:30.640 --> 00:33.400
The Earth revolves around the Sun.

00:33.400 --> 00:38.640
This heliocentric view challenged centuries of geocentric beliefs, setting the stage for

00:38.640 --> 00:46.280
a seismic shift in thinking, observation, experimentation, and the scientific method

00:46.280 --> 00:50.520
replaced reliance on ancient authorities.

00:50.520 --> 00:56.560
This new approach, advocated by figures like Francis Bacon, fostered a culture of inquiry

00:56.560 --> 00:59.320
and evidence-based reasoning.

00:59.320 --> 01:06.400
The principles of reason and scientific inquiry spilled over into philosophy and politics.

01:06.400 --> 01:12.920
Enlightenment thinkers like Voltaire embraced these ideas, advocating for liberty, progress,

01:12.920 --> 01:16.360
and rational government.

01:16.360 --> 01:20.920
The ripple effects of the scientific revolution were profound.

01:20.920 --> 01:26.560
Innovation, such as the sextant revolutionized navigation, expanding horizons in trade

01:26.560 --> 01:29.520
and exploration.

01:29.520 --> 01:36.880
The legacy of the scientific revolution is evident in today's technological landscapes.

01:36.880 --> 01:42.200
From the way we govern societies to how we perceive our place in the universe, the seeds

01:42.200 --> 01:46.600
planted during this era continue to influence us.

01:46.600 --> 01:52.880
So as we gaze through telescopes or debate ethics in science, remember, the roots of these

01:52.880 --> 01:57.040
modern marvels lie deep in the revolutionary soil of the past.

